author: HelloFresh
time required: 30 minutes
servings: 2
---

Take the @rump bistro steak{2} out of your fridge so it can come to room 
temperature and preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potato{1} into wedges 
about the size of your index finger (no need to peel). Halve, peel and thinly 
slice the @red onion{1} into half moons. Pop the wedges on a #baking tray{}, 
drizzle with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Roast on 
the top shelf of your oven for ~{15%minutes}. Then turn and add the onion. Roast 
for another ~{15%minutes}.

Trim the tops and bottoms off the @runner beans{1}, remove the stringy edges 
(a #peeler{} can be useful here) and chop into 2cm pieces. Halve the 
@red chilli{1/2} lengthways, remove the seeds and finely chop. Finely chop the 
@basil{1} and @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped, stalks and all). Pick the 
@mint{1}(leaves picked and finely chopped, stalks discarded).

Pop the basil, mint and parsley in a #small bowl{}. Add the chilli (use less if 
you don't like spice) and @olive oil{4%tbsp}. Add a splash of the @cider vinegar{} 
and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Mix together, taste and add more 
vinegar if desired, then set aside.

Put a drizzle of olive oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season each 
steak with a pinch of salt and black pepper. Once the pan is smoking hot, lay 
in the steak and cook for ~{2.5%minutes} on each side, then remove to a 
#cutting board{}, cover with #foil{} and rest for a few minutes.

> TIP: We like our steak medium-rare but if you like yours less pink, give it 
> 3 1/2 mins on each side for medium or 5 mins on each side for well-done.

While the steak is resting, quickly wipe out your frying pan with some 
#kitchen paper{} and pop it back on medium heat with a drizzle of olive oil. 
Add the runner beans, season with salt and black pepper and stir-fry until 
softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Thinly slice the steak. Serve on #plates{} with some chimichurri spooned on 
top and the wedges and runner beans on the side. Enjoy!

> TIP: Cutting the steak against the grain will make it more tender.